---
// TwoAIReview.astro — peer review from two independent AI models, side by side
// Anchor: review | Responsive two-column layout | No props
---

<section class="review-section">
  <p class="section-moral"><em>One witness is an anecdote; two are a review.</em></p>

  <h2 id="review">Peer review — two models, one repository</h2>

  <div class="review-grid">
    <!-- Column 1: Claude review -->
    <div class="review-column claude-review">
      <blockquote class="review-quote">
        <p>
          Aesop is that rare meta-project that earns its premise: an orchestration harness whose own commit history is its benchmark. The engineering instinct worth hiring is visible in the data: measure before believing (two A/B tests killed a fashionable hierarchical architecture the numbers didn't support), state moved off git into an event-sourced store when coordination outgrew it, secret-scanning gating every push. 130 merged PRs written substantially by the fleet itself — with the failures logged as carefully as the wins.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="review-attribution">— Claude (Anthropic), reviewing the repository it helps orchestrate.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Column 2: Gemini review -->
    <div class="review-column gemini-review">
      <blockquote class="review-quote">
        <p>
          Aesop is a compelling exercise in recursive engineering. By utilizing Claude Code to build and refine its own orchestration harness, the project demonstrates a sophisticated grasp of agentic workflows. I am particularly impressed by the decision to move away from a hierarchical dispatch model in favor of a lean, event-sourced SQLite state store; this reduces complexity while maintaining durability. The integration of pre-push security gates and real-time observability via the dashboard provides necessary guardrails for autonomous operations. While the "Haiku-first" cost strategy is technically sound, I would watch how the system handles emergent non-deterministic behavior as the codebase scales. Overall, it is a pragmatic, well-documented framework for anyone serious about production-grade agentic orchestration.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="review-attribution">— Gemini (Google), reviewing the aesop repository · gemini-flash-lite-latest</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .review-section {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-16);
  }

  /* Override shared section h2 to match TwoAIReview's smaller size */
  .review-section h2 {
    font-size: var(--text-2xl);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-10);
  }

  .review-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-8);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
  }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .review-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    }
  }

  .review-column {
    padding: var(--space-8);
    border-radius: 8px;
  }

  .claude-review,
  .gemini-review {
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .review-quote {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    color: var(--color-text);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
  }

  .review-quote p {
    margin: 0;
  }

  .review-attribution {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    font-style: italic;
    margin: 0;
    padding-top: var(--space-4);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding-top: var(--space-4);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
  }

  /* Focus ring support for accessibility */
  .review-column:focus-within {
    outline: var(--focus-ring);
    outline-offset: var(--focus-ring-offset);
  }

  /* Reduced motion: no transitions needed, no animations on first render */
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .review-column {
      transition: none;
    }
  }
</style>
